One-iteration Phase II convergence example
==========================================

Problem
-------
Minimize  -x1 - y1
Subject to
  x1 <= 5         (sub1 constraint)
  y1 <= 3         (sub2 constraint)
  x1 + y1 = 6     (coupling constraint, GLP_FX)
  x1, y1 >= 0

Known optimal
-------------
x1 = 3, y1 = 3
Objective = -(3 + 3) = -6

Code path exercised
-------------------
Because the coupling constraint is an equality and the objective equals
-(x1+y1) = constant on the feasible set, the restricted master is already
at its DW-relaxation optimum after Phase I.  Phase II finds no improving
columns on the first full iteration and converges immediately.

This exercises the fast-convergence branch in phase_2_iteration() where
the "I think we've converged" path is reached after a single Phase II
master solve with zero or degenerate column additions.
